  ('CISA-00623', 1, 'Medium', 'Audit Follow-up and Remediation', 'What is the MOST appropriate recommendation for the auditor to make?', 'To replace the general cybersecurity training with a highly specialized OT cybersecurity training program immediately.', 'To supplement the existing general cybersecurity training with OT-specific modules and simulations relevant to their roles and responsibilities.', 'To reduce the frequency of cybersecurity training for OT staff due to its complexity and potential disruption of operations.', 'To delegate the responsibility of providing OT cybersecurity training to external vendors without internal oversight.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): To supplement the existing general cybersecurity training with OT-specific modules and simulations relevant to their roles and responsibilities.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  