e, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Immediately re-test the access controls of the claims processing system to determine the full extent of the non-compliance. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Recommend that the system administrator immediately enable MFA for all users accessing the claims processing system. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Document the partial implementation of MFA and include it in the next scheduled audit report. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
  ('CISA-00625', 1, 'Medium', 'Audit Follow-up and Remediation', 'What should the auditor FIRST recommend regarding the identified vulnerability?', 'Conduct a penetration test to fully assess the remaining attack vectors and their potential impact.', 'Immediately report the findings to the Chief Information Security Officer (CISO) and request a complete system shutdown.', 'Request the system owner to revise the remediation plan to include comprehensive input validation for all attack vectors.', 'Issue a new audit finding indicating that the original vulnerability remains unresolved and requires further attention.', 'C', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (C): Request the system owner to revise the remediation plan to include comprehensive input validation for all attack vectors.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Con