r understanding of the tool''s capabilities. → This is incomplete or applies the wrong standard. It might address part of the issue but misses the full picture.  Option D: A comparison of the current security incident logs with previous audit findings. → While seemingly reasonable, this approach deviates from best practice and creates unnecessary risk or inefficiency.'),
  ('CISA-00633', 1, 'Medium', 'Audit Follow-up and Remediation', 'What should the auditor recommend as the PRIMARY improvement to the encryption implementation?', 'Implement stronger encryption algorithms (e.g., AES-256).', 'Rotate the encryption keys on a more frequent basis (e.g., monthly).', 'Store the encryption keys in a separate, more secure location, such as a hardware security module (HSM).', 'Implement access controls to restrict access to the server hosting the database and encryption keys.', 'C', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (C): Store the encryption keys in a separate, more secure location, such as a hardware security module (HSM).  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Implement stronger encryption algorithms (e.g., AES-256). → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without docum