 trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Mandate that all departments immediately delete any PII data that exceeds the most restrictive retention period found across all departmental schedules. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Conduct a comprehensive risk assessment to determine the potential impact of non-compliance on each department''s operations. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Implement a data loss prevention (DLP) system to automatically identify and delete PII data based on predefined retention rules. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.', 'Developing and implementing a centralized, organization-wide data retention policy is the MOST immediate recommendation because it establishes a consistent and compliant framework for managing PII across the entire institution. This addresses the root cause of the problem by replacing conflicting schedules with a unified approach that reflects regulatory obligations.', 'See reasoning above for explanation of correct vs incorrect choices', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Develop and implement a centralized, organization-wide data retention policy that aligns with regulatory requirements and supersedes all departmental schedules.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Mandate that all departments immediately delete any PII data that exceeds the most restrictive retention period found across all departmental schedules. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Conduct a comprehensive risk assessment to determine the potential impact of non-compliance on each department''s operations. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Implement a data loss prevention (DLP) system to automatically identify and delete PII data based on predefined retention rules. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
