ed approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Recommend immediate replacement of all legacy systems, regardless of cost, to minimize operational risk. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Directly interview IT staff to informally document the support processes for each legacy system. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Review the IT department''s budget to determine if sufficient funds are allocated for legacy system maintenance. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
  ('CISA-00806', 2, 'Medium', 'IT Portfolio Management', 'What should the auditor recommend FIRST?', 'Suggest re-evaluating the project prioritization criteria to incorporate the potential losses from performance degradation.', 'Advise the IT department to immediately deploy more server resources to handle the peak traffic.', 'Recommend implementing a web application firewall (WAF) to mitigate potential denial-of-service attacks.', 'Inform the Chief Technology Officer (CTO) about the performance issues and suggest expediting the database upgrade project.', 'A', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (A): Suggest re-evaluating the project prioritization criteria to incorporate the potential losses from performance degradation.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option B: Advise the IT department to immediately deploy more server re