ges and configurations. → This is incomplete or applies the wrong standard. It might address part of the issue but misses the full picture.  Option D: Periodic penetration testing of the production inventory management system. → While seemingly reasonable, this approach deviates from best practice and creates unnecessary risk or inefficiency.'),
  ('CISA-00881', 3, 'Hard', 'Change and Configuration Management', 'What is the auditor''s PRIMARY concern regarding the CI/CD pipeline?', 'The lack of rollback procedures in case of failed deployments.', 'Insufficient capacity planning for the e-commerce website infrastructure.', 'The absence of a pre-production environment that accurately simulates production load and data volumes.', 'Inadequate security testing integrated into the CI/CD pipeline.', 'C', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (C): The absence of a pre-production environment that accurately simulates production load and data volumes.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: The lack of rollback procedures in case of failed deployments. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process tha